{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e3b8bbaf-81a2-4a8c-9a1f-d223bf244f7b","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these locations:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates `.ips` or `.crash` files:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar for a formatted view.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — Disabled by default. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file typically appears in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **`log show`** — Check system logs for crash context:\n   ```bash\n   log show --predicate 'process == \"YourAppName\"' --last 10m\n   ```\n\nThe `.ips` crash report is usually your best bet — it includes the stack trace, signal info, and loaded images, and macOS generates it automatically with no setup needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1f28407a-bbb3-46a4-b129-ea5104456fd2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":302,"requestId":"2050:328887:7966E7:8BCD6A:69F01195"},"id":"7b227225-ec83-4e94-b72a-169ca74f20b4","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:47:08.970Z","parentId":"1403dddf-059d-40f8-ac4d-1bf659055b31"}
